Description: Sometimes parents just need to find a playground NOW! We're the app that helps them do that. Find nearby playgrounds wherever you go!
Headquarters Regions: East Coast, Southern US
Full Description: Sometimes parents just need to find a playground NOW! Play Across America is the solution. We help families quickly and easily find nearby playgrounds wherever they go, whether it's a new local playground, driving along a major interstate, in an airport or mall, or even on a military installation. As a military family and parents to four small children ourselves, we know what it's like when kids get restless and just need to burn off a little energy. In fact, that is precisely why we started Play Across America--we were moving from Kansas to Washington and were tired of stopping at truck stops. I asked a local about a playground when we stopped in Missoula, MT, and she directed us to the most amazing playground I'd seen up to that point--Dragon Hollow Playground. It was awesome and it was just a short drive from I-90! I knew at that moment that parents needed a national resource that could help them discover great places to play quickly and efficiently. I did a lot of research and couldn't find anything like what I wanted and started Play Across America as a hobby in August of 2012. After three years, we launched as a business in October 2015 and built out our free iPhone app and released it on March 17, 2016.  In the near future we hope to build out the Android app as well.

Description: Orthopaedic Spine Surgeon, Director of Scoliosis and Spine Associates, Clinical Associate Professor of Orthopaedic Surgery at N.Y.U School
Headquarters Regions: Greater New York Area, East Coast, Northeastern US
Full Description: For over thirty years in New York, we have been treating pediatric and adult patients with scoliosis, kyphosis and other spinal deformities and disorders. We pride ourselves on providing the highest level of care to our patients in a compassionate environment. Our surgeons. physicians and staff are professionals who use the latest technologies, surgical techniques and treatment options. We never lose sight of our first priority to care for our patients. We treat our patients as we would treat our own family. The philosophy of Scoliosis Associates involves a patient-centered approach to medicine. We strive to attain the trust and respect of our patients, and we educate our patients so that they can make informed decisions. In formulating our treatment plans, we also take into consideration each patient’s unique long-term goals, such as improvement of function in daily activities as well as appearance, in addition to traditional clinical goals such as correcting the curve in scoliosis. Balancing these two factors allows us to treat you with your best interests in mind.

Description: OCSC Sailing began in 1979, with one boat, a shed, and a simple idea: share the joy of sailing and take care of our clients
Headquarters Regions: San Francisco Bay Area, West Coast, Western US
Full Description: Ah, 1979. Carter was President, the Soviets invaded Afghanistan, radios blasted I Will Survive and My Sharona, everyone was talking about Kramer vs. Kramer, and seasoned sailor Anthony Sandberg had a white Dodge van and an idea: sailing was too good to be just the sport of the rich. So the man with a van borrowed a J/24, rented a shack on Alameda Estuary, and hung a shingle that read “Olympic Circle Sailing Club.” His vision was to teach sailing to students the same way he’d teach his friends. “I knew that if I had just one student, I would take such good care of them, they’d tell their friends. And that’s how they started the club,” Anthony recalls. Within a year of surviving on canned tuna and baked potatoes, Sandberg moved OCSC to an abandoned warehouse and the club had 100 members, hundreds of students, and a small fleet of Capri 14’s. Aspiring sailors were coming to him with what he recognized as cherished, closely held dreams. And to Anthony, part of respecting those dreams was democratizing what was perceived as an elitist, male-dominated sport: anyone, he reasoned, could sail, and women could skipper.
